title: Inequality
markdown:
# Inequality (!=)

 The **inequality (`!=`)** operator checks whether its two operands are not equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the [strict inequality](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Strict%5Finequality) operator, it attempts to convert and compare operands that are of different types.

## [Try it](#try%5Fit)

## [Syntax](#syntax)

```
x != y

```

## [Description](#description)

 The inequality operator checks whether its operands are not equal. It is the negation of the [equality](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Equality) operator so the following two lines will always give the same result:

```
x != y;

!(x == y);

```

For details of the comparison algorithm, see the page for the [equality](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Equality) operator.

 Like the equality operator, the inequality operator will attempt to convert and compare operands of different types:

```
3 != "3"; // false

```

 To prevent this, and require that different types are considered to be different, use the [strict inequality](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Strict%5Finequality) operator instead:

```
3 !== "3"; // true

```

## [Examples](#examples)

### [Comparison with no type conversion](#comparison%5Fwith%5Fno%5Ftype%5Fconversion)

```
1 != 2; // true
"hello" != "hola"; // true

1 != 1; // false
"hello" != "hello"; // false

```

### [Comparison with type conversion](#comparison%5Fwith%5Ftype%5Fconversion)

```
"1" != 1; // false
1 != "1"; // false
0 != false; // false
0 != null; // true
0 != undefined; // true
0 != !!null; // false, look at Logical NOT operator
0 != !!undefined; // false, look at Logical NOT operator
null != undefined; // false

const number1 = new Number(3);
const number2 = new Number(3);
number1 != 3; // false
number1 != number2; // true

```

### [Comparison of objects](#comparison%5Fof%5Fobjects)

```
const object1 = {
  key: "value",
};

const object2 = {
  key: "value",
};

console.log(object1 != object2); // true
console.log(object1 != object1); // false

```
